Best Practices include:

1. Designing Loosely Coupled Architectures Using IoC and DI

Theory
Loose coupling means components (classes, services, etc.) depend on abstractions (interfaces)
rather than concrete implementations.
Inversion of Control (IoC): The control of object creation and wiring is handed over to the
Spring container.
Dependency Injection (DI): Spring injects dependencies into your classes, rather than your
classes creating them.

Implementation
Use interfaces for dependencies:

public interface NotificationService {
    void send(String message);
}

@Service
public class EmailNotificationService implements NotificationService {
    public void send(String message) { /* ... */ }
}

Inject dependencies via constructor (preferred):

@Service
public class UserService {
    private final NotificationService notificationService;

    @Autowired
    public UserService(NotificationService notificationService) {
        this.notificationService = notificationService;
    }
}

Benefits:
Easy to swap implementations (e.g., switch from email to SMS).
Easier to test (can inject mocks or stubs).
Code is more modular and maintainable.

2. Writing Testable and Maintainable Code with Spring Core

Theory
Testable code is code that can be easily unit tested.
Maintainable code is code that is easy to understand, modify, and extend.

Implementation
Constructor injection makes it easy to inject mock dependencies for testing.

@Test
public void testUserService() {
    NotificationService mockService = Mockito.mock(NotificationService.class);
    UserService userService = new UserService(mockService);
    // test logic...
}
Use @Profile for test-specific beans:

@Service
@Profile("test")
public class MockNotificationService implements NotificationService {
    public void send(String message) { /* mock logic */ }
}

Keep beans small and focused (Single Responsibility Principle).
Use @Qualifier to resolve ambiguity when multiple beans of the same type exist.


3. Avoiding Common Pitfalls

a. Circular Dependencies
What is it?
When two or more beans depend on each other, causing a loop (e.g., A depends on B, B depends
on A).
Why is it bad?
Spring cannot resolve the dependencies and will throw an error.

How to avoid:
Rethink your design—break the cycle by introducing an interface or event.
Use setter injection if absolutely necessary (not recommended for required dependencies).

Example of a circular dependency:

@Component
public class A {
    @Autowired
    private B b;
}

@Component
public class B {
    @Autowired
    private A a;
}

Solution:
Refactor so that only one depends on the other, or use events/callbacks.

b. Excessive Dependencies

What is it?
When a class depends on too many other classes (sometimes called a "God object").
Why is it bad?
Hard to test, maintain, and understand.

How to avoid:
Apply the Single Responsibility Principle: each class should have one reason to change.
Split large classes into smaller, focused ones.
Limit the number of constructor parameters (ideally 3-5).

c. Field Injection

Why avoid?
Harder to test (can’t inject mocks easily).
Hides dependencies (not visible in constructor).

Best practice:
Use constructor injection for required dependencies.